metadata.name: Precision: angles #145
metadata.description:
This is the first hash-derived entry into my "Precisions" series.  I have been using Precisions as a meditative art practice where I focus on exact positioning of elements, less-emphasized colors, and repetition of geometric shapes.  

In "angles", each element is comprised of right triangles transformed over a common point.  I decided to bring some of the fragmentation from my previous project, "Restrictions", to produce irregular works.  I found beauty in that unpredictable asymmetry and feel it really enhances the structure of this piece.

metadata.name: Life has no scores #71
metadata.description:
We cannot compose life, at best we hum along to the melodies that life has been played in front of us. Looking back at the scores of our lives, the notations are never neatly noted, but fully felt.  Rewinding the songs of life are our memories, whether sad, happy, angry, or melancholy. It is not clear whether I am dreaming or awake, but our songs all do end. 

In this final drop (for ?), I have reused the first ever class calligraphy(){} I have written from my genesis drop “Nothing comes from nothing”. As time passes, 10 drops later, across almost to the year, I am grateful for the progress I have made, as an artist, and more importantly as a human. After all, what is behind the code of generative art is a human being. 

Scores of music, scrolls of calligraphy, calendar or diary, notating life, time passes, and changes are inevitable. Sometimes we sing louder in laughter and joy, sometimes we scribble in uneasiness, sometimes we just get lost in neon lights. Life goes on. You and me, all the same and yet different.  

There are too many friend artists, friend collectors, fxhash team members, to thank for helping me through this journey. I would like to pay homage to Rudxane in this work, who has taken me under his wings, mentoring and encouraging me in art as well as showing me some degen stuff on the side:-). This homage is not copy-minting, or copying of styles, which I do not have the coding skills to do so even if I wanted to. But it is the influence of taste in many works of Rudxane. In a vague but agreeable taste, I present to you Life has no scores. 

What I was taught was disrupted, and grid studies left unfinished, and oh do we have a BINGO?

Tested on Chrome. Other browsers may render different or not at all (firefox)

Press ‘2’ to save png.

Copyright (©) 2022 Jimi Wen
Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

metadata.name: n Forms #253
metadata.description:
Hand-scrawled documentation of abstract structures. A journal from another realm.

Press 's' to save an image while in full-screen mode.

If you want to increase the resolution of the saved image, add e.g. &size=2000 after the live/fullscreen view URL to render the canvas at that specific pixel width (default = browser sized). This will be dependent on your system specifications, but outputs of up to 8000px wide, or above, should be possible.

Usually loads best in Chrome

metadata.name: Artifice #290
metadata.description:
This series is is about playful obfuscation.

The fxtext article linked on the main profect goes more in-depth into what is meant by that, as well as the events that led to this collection.

5640 bytes of Vanilla JS with no libraries. Palettes make up a third of the code.

In live mode:
‘S’ : save as png (3000 × 3600)
’V’ : save as svg (without grain)

URL params in live mode:
‘g=n’ : no grain
‘g=p’ : paper grain
‘h=t’ : high resolution mode, 9000 ×10600 (Chrome only, and may take a moment)

For example, if you wanted paper grain in high resolution, append “&g=p&h=t” to the url in live mode.

After rendering with these params, tapping 'P' will then save a png with those settings applied.

metadata.name: Elo #115
cellular_collage #68
metadata.description:
Each token is a unique collage of two distinct Multi-Neighborhood Cellular Automata systems.

Click and drag to place noise on the canvas. Press the space bar to pause the simulation, and again to resume it. While paused, you can press "n" to advance the simulation by a single step.

metadata.name: EDDY #177
metadata.description:
An eddy is a circular movement of water counter to a main current. It reminds me of innovations in art, like a small countercurrent to the mainstream, surfacing new techniques and aesthetics. 

I hope that EDDY will brighten your days with its playful swirl of colors, inspired by the sea, the sky, the birds, and post-impressionist paintings.

Keyboard Controls:
[F] Fill the window.
[S] Save the current view in live mode as an image (default 1125x1500px).
[1] [2] [4] [6] Change resolution, 1.5K to 9K.
[R] Reverse course.

Made with p5js and shaders.

Created by elsif, 2022.12.

metadata.name: Ataraxis #372
metadata.description:
Ataraxis (or a broken volume renderer) is an exploration in balancing discomfort and calm. The piece generates spaces on the fly that are designed to elicit strange and uncomfortable feelings - like a desolate, alien dreamscape - claustrophobic, surreal, not quite real yet strangely recognisable. But the idea is that while these spaces feel uncomfortable, they're also strangely, antilogically calming. The idea is to elicit a sanguine emotion, to make the viewer feel calm in a strange place, and to lead them somewhere else.

This work is the culmination of many years of work researching volumetric rendering techniques. This token uses a raymarching technique that is intentionally broken in various ways.

Controls:
Double-click to download
&w=X&h=y to change the size of the piece
&dpr=x to change the resolution of the pice - higher resolutions will result in slightly different artworks as the browser attempts to compensate for the overlarge canvas
&fullscreen=true to change the token to display the full size of your browser. This may impact the rendering of the token, so use with caution

metadata.name: tratti #271
metadata.description:
"tratti" is an Italian word that has many different meanings. When we started working on this piece, we wanted to create something that combines our traits ("tratti" in Italian).
We had this urge to channel the turbulent times we're living in now into this artwork using just lines ("tratti" in Italian).

We don't know what to do now, we're here, and that's all that matters. We're here for our families, our friends, and our community. Like everything in life, there are joyful times and challenging times. We must accept happiness as something that is not constant but that we feel at times (a "tratti" in Italian).

With "tratti", we want to send a message to every disheartened human being: "Stay strong and never let anyone or anything crush the hope in you. Joyful times are around the corner".

metadata.name: Aquarelle #128
metadata.description:
Mimicking the art of watercolours.

Save as png:
Click “s”
or double click/tap

Resolution:
Default image width = 2000px and aspect ratio = 4:3.
Modify the image width between 2000px and 10000px by adding “&w=xxxx” to the url (e.g. &w=4000).
High resolutions are computationally expensive and may take a while.

Background:
The canvas background texture is visible by default. This can be toggled off by adding “&b=0” to the url.
The background scales with resolution to mimic a bigger canvas so it will look different at different resolutions.
At high resolutions a Moiré pattern may appear on the canvas background texture due to the way images are resized in the browser. It’s always recommended to download a full resolution version of the piece.

By KRANKARTA
Created on Firefox desktop 105.0 on 2022-11-11 in javascript and GLSL.
CC BY-NC-ND 4.0

metadata.name: Plottable Era: (I) Primitive #4
metadata.description:
'Plottable Era: (I) Primitive' is the first generator in the "Era" generators series, highlighting different periods and civilizations. This first series "Primitive" shows the beginning of mankind with people exploring the mountains and traveling on the sea during sunset.

The digital version simulates ink effects and adds a subtle animation over the water. Each outcome is also physically plottable with pens: A SVG file can be exported (right-click save) to plot the piece physically. The plots are designed to be executed in A4 format on either fountain pens (on white paper) or gel pens (Black / Blue).

Thanks to the utility token decoupling, you can get a physical version: the digital NFT is the recipe to a plottable art piece, owning it confers the right to plot or request a physical plot from @greweb (https://greweb.me/plots/nft). @greweb would use fountain pens but other plotting artists are free to achieve it with their own materials and ship to collectors – as long as NFT is owned at request time.

More details and Source code: https://github.com/gre/gre/tree/master/doodles/plottable-era-primitive

@greweb – 2022 – tech: WebGL + Rust + WASM – CC BY-SA 4.0 https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/

reserve is set to previous 2022 physical plot collectors.

metadata.name: Veils of Perception #22
metadata.description:
Through the veil of perception we do not see things as they are, for they are filtered by who we are. This work was created to produce "The Veil" for the Blind Gallery: Bear Market Edition.

- Use the "S" key to save a PNG image.
- Use the "P" key to export a print-quality image.

metadata.description:
Sketches of geometric shapes with scale symmetry.

"What does the mirror see when it looks in the mirror?"

--

- Press "S" to export a standard resolution image.
- Press "P" to export an hi-res image.
- Press "G" to toggle the grain.

metadata.name: Sprocket Factory #481
metadata.description:
Just an ordinary scene from a typical day, working as a Sprocket Factory engineer. Inspiration for this work is drawn from the composable nature of blockchain smart contracts and the flow of value between networks of autonomous machines and free-willed individuals.

"A Doodle, Ringer, and Fidenza walk into a Space Bar..."

- Live renderer best viewed in Chrome.
- Press "P" to export an PNG raster image (10k resolution.)
- Press "S" to export an SVG vector.
